
🔥 1. Cyber Security Vulnerabilities (5M)
Cyber Security Vulnerabilities are weaknesses or flaws in systems, networks, or applications that
can be exploited by attackers to gain unauthorized access or cause damage.
These vulnerabilities arise due to:
● Software bugs
● Misconfiguration
● Weak passwords
● Outdated systems
Examples:
● Malware
● Phishing attacks
● Ransomware
● Data breaches
Conclusion: Identifying and fixing vulnerabilities is essential to protect systems and sensitive data.



🔥 2. Access Control (5M)
Access Control is a security technique that restricts access to resources only to authorized users.
It ensures:
● Authentication (who you are)
● Authorization (what you can access)
Types:
● Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
● Mandatory Access Control (MAC)
● Discretionary Access Control (DAC)
● Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)
Importance:
● Prevents unauthorized access
● Protects sensitive data



🔥 3. Authentication & Types (5M)
Authentication is the process of verifying the identity of a user before granting access.
Steps:
● Identification
● Verification
● Validation
Types of Authentication:
● Single Factor Authentication
● Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)
● Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)
● Biometric Authentication
● One-Time Password (OTP)
Conclusion: Authentication ensures only authorized users can access systems.



🔥 4. SSL Authentication (5M)
SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) is a security protocol used to encrypt communication between a client
and a server.
Working:
● Establishes secure connection
● Encrypts data transmission
● Uses digital certificates
Features:
● Data confidentiality
● Data integrity
● Authentication of server
Example: HTTPS websites use SSL for secure browsing.




